<TITLE> Former Kenya leader Moi in hospital with back pains </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NAIROBI, Jan 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Former Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi has been admitted to hospital in the capital Nairobi after suffering back pains, his press secretary said on Monday. "He was admitted this morning with lower back pains, and the doctor says he expects (Moi) to be in hospital for the next two or so days," press secretary Lee Njiru said. Moi stepped down in 2002 after a 24-year rule characterised by graft which nearly ruined east Africa's biggest economy. President Mwai Kibaki overwhelmingly beat Moi's chosen successor in elections in 2002 but the self-styled "professor of politics" surprised many by backing Kibaki's bid for re-election in December. Kibaki's disputed re-election a month ago triggered weeks of chaos after the opposition claimed that he had stolen the election. Around 800 people have died and at least a quarter of a million have been displaced in the fighting. In July last year Kibaki appointed Moi, once his bitter foe, as a special envoy to Sudan to help facilitate a peace deal in southern Sudan, where Kenya has strong economic interes
